# Testing and verification — terminal use

## Quality gate (the **only** chained verification)

When running the full **quality gate** — ESLint, TypeScript check, Stylelint, and unit tests — use **one** terminal invocation with a single chained command so the shell stops on the first failure and you avoid extra round-trips:

`yarn lint && yarn lint:types && yarn lint:style && yarn test:unit`

**Exception**: if you are **debugging** a specific failing step, run that command **alone** (and any narrower follow-ups) until it passes, then re-run the full chained gate before commit or changelog edits.

This quartet is the **only** case where these four Yarn scripts may be combined in one shell line. Do not extend this chain with `yarn build`, Playwright, or Storybook.

## Everything else — one command per terminal

Run each of these in its **own** terminal invocation (do not chain them with each other or with the quality gate in the same line):

- `yarn build`
- `yarn test:component`
- `yarn test:e2e`

Keep logs isolated for readability and easier failure triage.

## Reporting

When reporting progress, list results in execution order (for the quality gate, you may report one combined pass/fail, or break out the first failing step if the chain stopped early).
